John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 alumni across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further higher education, chosen careers and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector able to develop and adopt a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and demanded subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will come to his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will come to the heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t rely on English alone if we want to build relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages scored the highest.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained the highest Chinese-lauded grade, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish obtained the highest grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as fundamental skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject choice are considered at the same level as STEM (Science, Technology, Technique and Mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason, language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of multiple languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a viable job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff specializing in this area.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need for success, whatever their future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
