"However, we do not see any compliant response from the US," he said.
“Without trust in the United States there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to unilaterally disarm first.”
Although Ri re-used the note of complaints about Washington’s resistance to “phased” denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded based on gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization altogether as Pyongyang has already done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The US insists on having ‘denuclearization first’ and increasing the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner, and even opposes the ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our mistrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader had announced at the U.N. earlier this week.
The minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the counterpart of this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was markedly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korean missiles after “the president of evil” Trump called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the disarmament path, but said much more needs to be done and that the sanctions will remain in place until North Korea's denuclearization.
Trump said on Wednesday he did not have a deadline, saying "whether it will take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
Cine and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “compliance with Security Council sanctions must continue forcefully and without exception until complete, final and ascertained denuclearization is achieved.”
