Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counter the growing culture of studying for whole nights powered by caffeine.
A university scholar noted that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He had the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“A girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, when I’m in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the “white night to study” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being an ever-growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and good quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, anxiety, he explained and even should serve to avoid gaining weight as lack of sleep takes the brain into starvation mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his lectures last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar program of study before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm for when they have to go to bed, as well as when they have to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to falling asleep problems.
