What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that sees the performance of a remarkable roster of stars and has an equally remarkable mission: to end poverty in the world.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people pouring into the Great Lawn of Central Park not only to enjoy performances like those of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also an awareness about the real purpose of the event, to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international support group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the concert audience had to complete a series of tasks, or “actions” such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful way that would help raise awareness about their goal of eradicating poverty.
But, to be precise, how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been now that there are 12 years left to achieve the goal set?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really a genuine way to persuade people to call for action, or is it just another example of so-called “clicktivism” – people who feel like they’re really making a difference by simply signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have registered more than 19 million “shares” of its supporters, working for a variety of purposes.
It states that these actions have helped to urge world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, aimed at influencing the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements stemming from their actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or used as funds.
The group estimates that to date, protected capital funds have had a direct impact on some 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of UK-based investors and performers committed to “helping children grow to their full potential,” with the promise to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help eliminate malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments, and Global Citizens just like you, we can make social injustice or malnutrition a footnote in history,” Tracey Ullman, an ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions were implemented calling on the UK to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, Power of Nutrition, that will reach 5 million women and children through nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the FAQs on his website, he asked, “What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and difficult journey – sometimes we will fall and we will fail.
But, like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
