Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the findings can reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawns, and how to best maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and the UK has declined significantly over the past century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting trespoli and ruining habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquito-killing paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to grabbing a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to spot insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect triplets, and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization even established Scotland’s first bat-only reserve at the Threave estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
