The USA team has been trying all weekend to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. Captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance by his team: “I’m proud of these guys because they fought.
At some point this morning we put pressure on the Europe team.
We threw this opportunity away.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 of his players performed very well.
I'll work with the American PGA and the Ryder Cup committee and we'll move on.
I'm fond of these 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
We've put it all together.
They played better than us.”
Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tide in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, suggesting a decrease in concentration, are evident in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom stretches for about 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a low-high concentration off Hillsborough County, from a low-high concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, from a low-high concentration to a high-high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, from a low-high concentration to a high-high concentration in the county.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, there were no reports of any cases in Northwest Florida.
